To derive point estimates and respective 95% confidence intervals for the parameters of interest, we employ a Markov Chain Monte Carlo procedure that allows us to calculate the median and the confidence intervals of the posterior distributions of \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym} 
				\usepackage{amsfonts} 
				\usepackage{amssymb} 
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$\delta _{a}, \delta _{a}^{Covid}$\end{document}δa,δaCovid, and θi, using as model Eqs. (6) and (7)23. We draw 100,000 samples from the joint posterior distribution and use 50 independent chains. The burn in interval is fixed at 20,000, and the thinning interval is 30. Convergence is checked (and satisfied) visually with Gelman-Rubin diagnostic. Our estimates are robust to the definitions of alternative distributions of the priors.

